To encrypt the message "HELLO" using the Hill cipher with the given matrix key, we first need to convert the letters to their corresponding numerical values (A=0, B=1, ..., Z=25). For "HELLO", we have:

H = 7
E = 4
L = 11
L = 11
O = 14

Since the matrix key is a 2x2 matrix, we need to break the message into pairs of letters. In this case, we have "HE" and "LL". If the message had an odd number of letters, we would need to add an extra letter (usually 'X' or 'Z') to make the last pair.

Now, we will multiply the matrix key by the numerical values of the letter pairs:

For "HE":
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 \\
3 & 5
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
7 \\
4
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
15 \\
37
\end{pmatrix}
$$

For "LL":
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 \\
3 & 5
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
11 \\
11
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
33 \\
88
\end{pmatrix}
$$

Now, we need to take the resulting values modulo 26 to get the numerical values of the ciphertext letters:

For "HE":
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
15 \\
37
\end{pmatrix}
\mod{26}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
15 \\
11
\end{pmatrix}
$$

For "LL":
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
33 \\
88
\end{pmatrix}
\mod{26}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
7 \\
12
\end{pmatrix}
$$

Finally, we convert the numerical values back to letters:

15 = P
11 = L
7 = H
12 = M

So, the encrypted message is "PLHM".
